<H1>Why Logarithms?</H1>




It turns out that the only (non-zero differentiable) functions with the
key property <P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<IMG
 WIDTH="259" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
src =  "img1.gif"
 ALT="$\displaystyle f(xy) = f(x) + f(y)\qquad(*)$">
</DIV><P></P>
are logarithmic
functions.  To see this we derive a differential equation for <IMG
 WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="41" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
src =  "img2.gif"
 ALT="$ f$">
whose solution is a logarithm.  Differentiating in <IMG
 WIDTH="33" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
src =  "img3.gif"
 ALT="$ (*)$"> with
respect to <IMG
 WIDTH="19" HEIGHT="22" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
src =  "img4.gif"
 ALT="$ x$"> gives
<P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<IMG
 WIDTH="377" HEIGHT="72" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
src =  "img5.gif"
 ALT="$\displaystyle yf'(xy) = f'(x)\quad\Longrightarrow\quad f'(xy) = \frac{f'(x)}{y}.$">
</DIV><P></P>
Similarly, differentiating with respect to <IMG
 WIDTH="18" HEIGHT="39" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
src =  "img6.gif"
 ALT="$ y$"> gives
<P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<IMG
 WIDTH="376" HEIGHT="72" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
src =  "img7.gif"
 ALT="$\displaystyle xf'(xy) = f'(y)\quad\Longrightarrow\quad f'(xy) = \frac{f'(y)}{x}.$">
</DIV><P></P>
Hence
<P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<IMG
 WIDTH="142" HEIGHT="72" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
src =  "img8.gif"
 ALT="$\displaystyle \frac{f'(x)}{y} = \frac{f'(y)}{x}.$">
</DIV><P></P>
In the special case <IMG
 WIDTH="56" HEIGHT="39" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
src =  "img9.gif"
 ALT="$ y=1$"> this turns into
<P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<IMG
 WIDTH="136" HEIGHT="72" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
src =  "img10.gif"
 ALT="$\displaystyle f'(x) = \frac{f'(1)}{x}.$">
</DIV><P></P>
From <IMG
 WIDTH="33" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
src =  "img3.gif"
 ALT="$ (*)$"> if follows that <IMG
 WIDTH="84" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
src =  "img11.gif"
 ALT="$ f(1) = 0$">.  The solution of this
initial value problem is
<P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<IMG
 WIDTH="205" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
src =  "img12.gif"
 ALT="$\displaystyle f(x) = C\ln x = \log_b x$">
</DIV><P></P>
where <IMG
 WIDTH="84" HEIGHT="27" ALIGN="BOTTOM" BORDER="0"
src =  "img13.gif"
 ALT="$ b = e^{1/C}$"> and  <IMG
 WIDTH="95" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
src =  "img14.gif"
 ALT="$ C= f'(1)$"> is an arbitrary constant.  

<P>
<BR>

<P>
So only logarithms work.  However, if you want to settle for
properties that are more complicated than <IMG
 WIDTH="33" HEIGHT="44" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
src =  "img3.gif"
 ALT="$ (*)$"> there are other
possibilities.  For example, you may want to think about how to
construct a slide rule based on the identity <P></P>
<DIV ALIGN="CENTER">
<IMG
 WIDTH="361" HEIGHT="67" ALIGN="MIDDLE" BORDER="0"
src =  "img15.gif"
 ALT="$\displaystyle \sin x \sin y =
\frac{1}{2}[\cos(x-y) - \cos(x+y)].$">
</DIV><P></P>

